               <desc type="site-data">
                  <p xml:lang="en" source="#bibl000294-1">The Qixia Monastery is a Buddhist monastery complex located in Qixia district, Nanjing municipality, Jiangsu province. It was constructed from the residence of the recluse Ming Sengshao in 489 under the <term ref="/keyword/000068">Southern Qi dynasty</term> (Wu and Chen 1994, online edition). At the beginning of the <term ref="/keyword/000082">Tang dynasty</term>, the emperor Gaozu (r. 618-626) renamed it Gongde Monastery and built 49 more subsidiary buildings. Because of its grand scale, the monastery, together with Lingyan Monastery in Shandong, Yuquan Monastery in Jingzhou, and Guoqing Monastery in Zhejiang, was known as one of the Four Great Forests [of Buddhism] (Ren and Yang 1989). It was later renamed Yinjun Qixia (“Recluse of Qixia”) Monastery because Tang emperor Gaozong wrote a stele inscription for Ming Sengshao. It was subsequently called Miaoyin Monatery in <term ref="/keyword/000077">Southern Tang</term> and Puyun Monatery, Qixia Chan Monastery, Jingde qixia Monastery, and Huxue Monastery during <term ref="/keyword/000074">Song dynasty</term> (Wu and Chen 1994, online edition). It was renamed Qixia Monastery in 1392, and the timber buildings were destroyed by war in 1855 (Wu and Chen 1994).</p>
                  <p xml:lang="zh-Hant" source="#bibl000294-1">棲霞寺位于江蘇省南京市，是建于<term ref="/keyword/000068">南齊</term>永明七年（489）的一座寺院 ，由隱士明僧紹的舍宅改建而成 (Wu and Chen 1994)。唐高祖將棲霞寺改名功德寺，並增建殿堂49所，規模宏大，與山東靈岩寺、荊州（今湖北）玉泉寺、浙江國清寺並稱天下四大叢林 (Ren and Yang 1989, online edition)。後因唐高宗題寫明征君（即明僧紹）碑文改名爲隱君棲霞寺。<term ref="/keyword/000077">南唐</term>改名妙音寺，<term ref="/keyword/000074">宋代</term>先後改名爲普雲寺、棲霞禅寺、景德棲霞寺、虎穴寺(Wu and Chen 1994)。<term ref="/keyword/000051">明</term>1392年複名棲霞寺，最終大部分建築于<term ref="/keyword/000070">清</term>1855年毀于戰火 (Wu and Chen 1994, online edition)。</p>
               </desc>
